         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s1">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Eight years ago, <b=
>Cathleen Chaffee</b>, the chief curator of the Buffalo AKG,  was alerted t=
o an extraordinary windfall. <b>Marisol</b>, the elusive, glamorous, monony=
mous, Paris-born artist=E2=80=94who attained worldwide celebrity in the 196=
0s before fading into obscurity=E2=80=94had bequeathed to the museum some 1=
00 sculptures, 600 works on paper, and 6,000 photographs, most of which had=
 been collecting dust in the artist=E2=80=99s Tribeca loft at the time of h=
er death. <br/><br/>Chaffee decided to mount a retrospective, committing th=
e museum to funding the time-consuming work of sorting through Marisol=E2=
=80=99s sprawling and largely undocumented oeuvre. The museum would have to=
 unpack and photograph hundreds of art works and determine when they were m=
ade, whether they=E2=80=99d ever been in a gallery show, and their relation=
 to other works. Moreover, Marisol=E2=80=99s dealer,
<b>Sidney Janis</b>, had died in 1989, leaving Chaffee the additional chall=
enge of cataloging a large body of work by an artist who had no gallery rep=
resentation to provide contextual clues.<br/></td>
         </tr>
