         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s12">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The poor response t=
o this new phase of her work, which she showed at Sidney Janis Gallery in 1=
973, might have crushed a lesser artist more dependent upon public approval=
=2E Instead, Marisol charted a path gui=
ded by her own interests. She continue=
d to make public monuments, and her sculptures took on a more reverential t=
one. At the Buffalo AKG, the retrospective culminates with a room of tribut=
es to <b>Georgia O=E2=80=99Keeffe</b>, <b>Desmond Tutu</b>, and the <b>Roeb=
ling </b>family that built the Brooklyn Bridge. <br/><br/>The finale of the=
 show is a testament to Marisol=E2=80=99s independence and perseverance. An=
 assemblage inspired by <b>John John</b>=E2=80=99s famous salute to his fat=
her=E2=80=99s funeral cort=C3=A8ge is now worlds away from Pop art. It=E2=
=80=99s elegiac and bittersweet. Like much of her work, it remains intrigui=
ngly, and deliberately, hard to define. Marisol
either made enough money from her sales in the =E2=80=9960s or had enough r=
esources from her family to not have to worry about pandering to collectors=
 or the art media. She traveled and continued to work. She didn=E2=80=99t s=
o much walk away from the world as the world walked away from her. There=E2=
=80=99s no evidence it bothered her at all. <br/></td>
         </tr>
